 ESKOM has appointed it’s chief financial officer (CFO) Calib Cassim as the acting CEO. This comes after the unexpected departure of Andre de Ruyter on Wednesday, 22 February. Eskom spokesman Sikhonathi Mantshantsha said Cassim would assume the position with immediate effect. “Mr Cassim will lead the Eskom management team until further notice,” said Mantshantsha. Cassim was appointed as the power utility’s CFO in November 2018 after serving as acting CFO from July 2017. ALSO READ:Farmers relieved after escaped lioness found “He is a registered Chartered Accountant (SA) and holds a master’s degree in business leadership (MBL). With over 20 years of service in Eskom." "His qualifications and extensive experience have provided Cassim with a deep understanding and appreciation of the Eskom business and the electricity industry, especially regarding the challenges facing the financing of operations and future expansion of the industry,” said Mantshantsha. He further thanked Cassim’s family for permitting him to assume the additional responsibilities and is grateful to him for stepping up to the role. De Ruyter, who was initially set to leave Eskom at the end of March after resigning last year December, shocked the public when it was announced that he was stepping down with immediate effect. This followed a damning  interview in which De Ruyter accused a senior politician of corruption including the governing party. 